What is a cryptocurrency payment gateway?

A crypto payment processor is a tool that allows businesses to accept payments in cryptocurrency for their products or services. It acts as a mediator between the buyer, the seller, and the blockchain network, ensuring the transaction is completed securely and efficiently.

How does a cryptocurrency payment gateway work?

Letâ€™s investigate why businesses need a crypto payment gateway to accept coins using BitHideâ€™s flow as an example.

Businesses that want to accept coins must incorporate the cryptocurrency gateway into their platform or application. Otherwise, there is no way to generate multiple unique addresses for cryptocurrency payments. In the case of BitHide, you install the software onto your server and connect the tool to your website or app.

Afterward, you can start accepting coins. Investigate how it works.

  • Step 1. The buyer selects cryptocurrency as the payment method at checkout and initiates the payment.
  • Step 2. The gateway generates a payment address for the buyer to send the cryptocurrency.
  • Step 3. The buyer sends the required amount of cryptocurrency to the payment address generated by the gateway.
  • Step 4. The processor verifies the transaction and sends a confirmation to the seller.
  • Step 5. The gateway transfers the cryptocurrency to the sellerâ€™s wallet and stores the transaction data on the sellerâ€™s server.

However, crypto payment processors can grant other perks apart from serving regular transactions. For example, BitHide assures the complete anonymity of the transactions, so you and your clients will remain unknown if you keep your private keys safe. This is thanks to the combined usage of TOR and VPN. Additionally, the tool helps simplify accounting and the management of multi-merchant accounts.

Are crypto payment gateways safe?

Although many gateways claim the safety of crypto payments, itâ€™s not that easy. Generally, you can consider crypto gateways safe. However, it doesnâ€™t mean that no third parties access your data. Moreover, it doesnâ€™t mean your walletâ€™s structure is impeccable. Look how it works.

There are two types of gateways. Some store data on cloud servers. Others do that on private clientsâ€™ servers. In the former case, the gatewaysâ€™ clients donâ€™t possess the data but can only access it with their private keys. Cloud providers, in turn, are obligated to share this data with legal bodies upon request. This is called KYC/AML verification. In the latter case, your data is stored on your private servers, so only you are its owner. Again, this means only you decide whether it must comply with KYC/AML.

As for the walletâ€™s structure, there is another situation. Although blockchain transactions are considered untraceable, itâ€™s not true. Only a few gateways can mess up the trace in such a way that no third parties can decipher it. For instance, BitHide uses the Dark Wing technology based on the simultaneous handling of VPN and TOR. This allows keeping your wallet safe.

What is the Dark Wing technology?

BitHide crypto payment gateway solution makes transactions anonymous using the Dark Wing technology. This technology consists of 2 stages of hiding your real IP address.

First, the transaction data is transmitted to the TOR network. They go through a chain of 3 or more addresses, hiding your real IP. The disadvantage of this system is that the blockchain network blocks most of the TOR IP addresses. We were the first to solve this problem, by adding the 2nd stage of encryption - VPN.

From the TOR network, your transactions are transmitted to the servers of VPN service providers. Their IP is no longer blocked by blockchain nodes, and you can freely use an anonymous crypto payment gateway.

For each new transaction, the Dark Wing changes its IP address for both, TOR and VPN. This way, your transactions cannot be placed into a single wallet, based on the IP address.

The Dark Wing technology - is the combination of 2 encryption systems. It allows you to use the advantages of TOR and VPN, canceling out their disadvantages.

As a result, combining crypto addresses into a single wallet becomes literally impossible.
